                  <Text layoutX="62.0" layoutY="191.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="In programming, control structures determine the flow of execution in a program. Rather than executing every line in sequence, control structures allow programmers to make decisions, repeat actions, or jump to specific points in the code. This chapter explores how C allows us to implement decision-making using various control structures such as if, else, and switch." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
